article.headline: DeForge scores career-high 31 in loss
article.linkText: Balanced Liberty deal Phoenix fourth straight loss
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Crystal Robinson's return was just what the New
York Liberty needed.

Vickie Johnson had 17 points and five assists, and Robinson, who
missed the previous six games due to a broken right pinkie, scored
16 points to lead the Liberty to a 77-69 victory over the Phoenix
Mercury on Sunday.

"Crystal's a competitor," New York interim coach Pat Coyle
said. "We missed her energy, but more importantly we missed her
defensive presence."

Elena Baranova had 12 points and 10 rebounds, and La'Keisha
Frett added 10 points in her Liberty debut.

Anna DeForge scored a career-high 31 points, and Diana Taurasi
had 14 points and seven rebounds for the Mercury in her first game
at Madison Square Garden.

DeForge single-handedly kept Phoenix in the game after Shameka
Christon's three-point play stretched New York's lead to 45-30 just
under three minutes into the second half. DeForge accounted for all
of the Mercury's scoring during a 17-6 run over a five-minute
stretch that cut the deficit to four with 10:54 remaining in the
game. However, that was the closest Phoenix got.

"She has done that for us all year," Taurasi said. "A lot of
people sleep on her, but Anna's been giving us that all year. She
has been the consistent one on this team."

Robinson followed DeForge's spurt with two straight baskets,
pushing New York's lead back to eight and starting a 14-6 run that
extend the cushion to 12. Phoenix didn't get closer than six the
rest of the way.

New York won for the second time in three games since Coyle
replaced the fired Richie Adubato after the Liberty lost eight of
their previous nine.

"I thought our execution was much better," Coyle said. "That
is something that we've really been focusing on. We pushed the ball
much better in transition."

Despite their struggles since opening the season 6-1, the
fifth-place Liberty (9-10) are just two games behind the Eastern
Conference-leading Charlotte Sting.

"We can't worry about what anyone else does," Robinson said.
"We have to take care of our own business."

Phoenix shot just 36 percent from the floor, including 21
percent (4-for-19) on 3-pointers. The Mercury have lost four
straight, and six of eight overall after losing five of seven on a
12-day road trip. They also remained winless in eight trips to New
York.

DeForge finished with the Mercury's highest total since Brandy
Reed scored 32 at Charlotte on June 22, 2000.

"Anna played great," Phoenix coach Carrie Graf said. "She hit
big shots for us. She got us rolling there offensively for a while.
Unfortunately, we didn't shoot the ball great."

Taurasi, who received a loud ovation during player
introductions, was just 4-for-16 from the floor.

"It was great," the former Connecticut star said of playing at
Madison Square Garden. "The atmosphere out there. You could see a
lot of people. It was something different.

"I wish we could've got a win, but it didn't happen. They did a
good job. They're veterans, a good defensive team."

Although the injury-plagued Liberty were missing two more
players -- reserves DeTrina White and Erin Thorn -- they did have
three fresh players available against the Mercury. In addition to
Robinson, Frett was one of two players signed to seven-day
contracts in the previous two days. Linda Frohlich, signed on
Saturday, did not play.

White was recovering from a mild concussion sustained in the
loss to Washington on Thursday, and Thorn had back spasms. The
Liberty were also missing Tari Phillips (broken right hand) and Ann
Wauters (broken bone in right foot).

Johnson put the Liberty ahead 8-6 with a layup 4:15 into the
game, and they led 39-26 at halftime.
